04972nam a22005415i 9780226322193DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20162016ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226322193  a(DE-B1597)523537  a(OCoLC)945447612  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aF869.L89bJ575 2016eb 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a305.892/40794942231 aTavory, Iddo, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSummoned :bIdentification and Religious Life in a Jewish Neighborhood /cIddo Tavory. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (224 p.) :b3 halftones, 3 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1 Toward a Sociology of Summoning -- t2 From Ethnic Enclave to Religious Destination -- t3 Organizational Entanglements -- t4 Edicts and Interaction in Synagogue Life -- t5 The Buzz of Difference -- t6 Situational Boundaries and Balancing Acts -- t7 The Neighborhood as Moral Obstacle Course -- t8 The Density of Worlds -- tAppendix: Summoned and Abductive Analysis -- tNotes -- tGlossary -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOn a typical weekday, men of the Beverly-La Brea Orthodox community wake up early, beginning their day with Talmud reading and prayer at 5:45am, before joining Los Angeles’ traffic. Those who work “Jewish jobs”—teachers, kosher supervisors, or rabbis—will stay enmeshed in the Orthodox world throughout the workday. But even for the majority of men who spend their days in the world of gentiles, religious life constantly reasserts itself. Neighborhood fixtures like Jewish schools and synagogues are always after more involvement; evening classes and prayers pull them in; the streets themselves seem to remind them of who they are. And so the week goes, culminating as the sabbatical observances on Friday afternoon stretch into Saturday evening. Life in this community, as Iddo Tavory describes it, is palpably thick with the twin pulls of observance and sociality. In Summoned, Tavory takes readers to the heart of the exhilarating—at times exhausting—life of the Beverly-La Brea Orthodox community. Just blocks from West Hollywood’s nightlife, the Orthodox community thrives next to the impure sights, sounds, and smells they encounter every day. But to sustain this life, as Tavory shows, is not simply a moral decision they make. To be Orthodox is to be constantly called into being. People are reminded of who they are as they are called upon by organizations, prayer quorums, the nods of strangers, whiffs of unkosher food floating through the street, or the rarer Anti-Semitic remarks. Again and again, they find themselves summoned both into social life and into their identity as Orthodox Jews. At the close of Tavory’s fascinating ethnography, we come away with a better understanding of the dynamics of social worlds, identity, interaction and self—not only in Beverly-La Brea, but in society at large.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aJewszCaliforniazLos AngelesxIdentity. 0aOrthodox JudaismzCaliforniazLos Angeles. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  areligious studies, religion, faith, belief, jewish, jews, judaism, neighborhood, locale, location, geography, community, beverly la brea, orthodox, talmud, prayers, daily life, tradition, culture, cultural, los angeles, commute, workday, workplace, gentiles, school, synagogue, sabbatical, holy day, west hollywood, california, kosher, anti semitic, ethnography, ethnographic.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311071098408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUrban Studies